{"id":"1607.06412","submitter":"Allan Walstad","authors":"Allan Walstad","title":"A Critical Reexamination of the Electrostatic Aharonov-Bohm Effect","comments":"7 pages plus two figures. The manuscript version of a paper published\n  in the International Journal of Theoretical Physics. Any reference to (or\n  quotation from) this paper should be to the published version","journal-ref":"Walstad, A.: Int. J. Theor. Phys. 49, 2929-2934 (2010)","doi":"10.1007/s10773-010-0485-0","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  This paper undertakes a critical reexamination of the electrostatic version\nof the Aharonov-Bohm (\"AB\") effect. The conclusions are as follows: 1. Aharonov\nand Bohm's 1959 exposition is invalid because it does not consider the\nwavefunction of the entire system, including the source of electrostatic\npotential. 2. As originally proposed, the electrostatic AB effect does not\nexist. Perhaps surprisingly, this conclusion holds despite the relativistic\ncovariance of the electromagnetic four-potential combined with the\nwell-established magnetic AB effect. 3. Although the authors attempted, in a\n1961 paper, to demonstrate that consideration of the entire system would not\nchange their result, they inadvertently assumed the desired outcome in their\nanalysis. 4. Claimed observations of the electrostatic AB effect or an analogue\nthereof are shown to be mistaken.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 21 Jul 2016 18:09:58 GMT"}],"update_date":"2016-07-22"}
