{"id":"1607.06419","submitter":"Allan Walstad","authors":"Allan Walstad","title":"Further Considerations Regarding the Aharonov-Bohm Effect and the\n  Wavefunction of the Entire System","comments":"8 pages plus 3 figures. Published in the International Journal of\n  Theoretical Physics (Springer). All references should be to the published\n  version","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1007/s10773-016-3239-9","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  In an earlier paper it was demonstrated that the hypothesized electrostatic\nversion of the Aharonov-Bohm (\"AB\") effect does not exist. The conclusion\nfollows straightforwardly once one recognizes that interference takes place in\nthe configuration space of the entire system, including the experimental\napparatus, and the wavefunction of the apparatus cannot be ignored. Two\nadditional results are presented here. 1. Observations of interference that had\nbeen attributed to an analogue of the electrostatic AB effect (or \"scalar\neffect\") are actually due to a magnetic AB effect. 2. In the original magnetic\nAB effect itself, there is no phase shift if it is possible effectively to\nshield the solenoid from the influence of the passing electron. This result is\nnot in conflict with the landmark experiments of Tonomura and colleagues if\nWang's recent claim is correct, that superconductive shielding could not have\nisolated the toroidal magnet from the magnetic pulse of the passing electron.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 21 Jul 2016 18:23:48 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Thu, 15 Dec 2016 17:52:28 GMT"}],"update_date":"2016-12-16"}
